The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                               SPORT BRIEFS
                                                  Amritraj enters  2nd round  Manchester: Prakash Amritraj saw off a strong challenge from Briton Chris Eaton to record a thrilling win in the opening round of the euro 30,000 Aegon Pro-Series ATP Challenger event here Wednesday. After losing the first set, the fifth seed came back strongly to beat local player 4-6, 6-3, 6-4 to advance to the second round of the grass court event.  Somdev up  Aptos (US): Somdev Dev Varman began his hardcourt season by defeating American wild card Lestor Cook 7-6(9-7), 6-2 in the first round of the $75,000 ATP Challenger event here.
    Shuttlers excel  New Delhi: India began their Asian Junior Badminton championships campaign on a resounding note with four out of five shuttlers coming up with easy wins in their singles opening round matches in Kuala Lumpur. H.S. Prannoy in men rsquo;s singles and P.C. Thulasi, Rane Saili and N. Sikki Reddy in women rsquo;s singles advanced to the second round.  Dhanraj upset  New Delhi: Former India hockey captain Dhanraj Pillay has criticised the newly-formed Hockey India for joining hands with erstwhile Indian Hockey Federation chief K.P.S. Gill and said the recent development is disheartening. He also criticised the IOA for appointing Spaniard Jose Brasa as the coach of the national team without consulting the selection committee members.  London GP  London: Asafa Powell will race against world-record holder Usain Bolt in the 100-metre race at next week rsquo;s London Grand Prix. The London GP is scheduled for July 24 and 25.  Ban reduced  Nyon: Uefa reduced Didier Drogba rsquo;s Champions League ban Wednesday from four matches to three after his foul-mouthed rant at the referee after Chelsea rsquo;s semi-final elimination in May. Uefa rsquo;s appeals body lowered the ban after the Chelsea striker pleaded his case in person alongside teammate Jose Bosingwa at a closed-door hearing. A suspended ban for another two games is still in place.  Iraq cleared  Kuala Lumpur: Iraq can start hosting matches for its national team and club sides in Asian continental competitions after a decision announced Wednesday by the Asian Football Confederation.  The AFC cleared the city of Arbil to host matches.  In trouble  Rio de Janeiro: Former Barcelona and Brazil striker Romario was arrested Tuesday for neglecting to make alimony payments to first wife Monica Santoro, Brazilian media reported. Romario, who helped Brazil win their fourth World Cup title in the US in 1994, might have to spend the night in a police cell, media reports said.  
